Look for spp crossing borders

library(tidyverse)
library(terra)
library(sf)
library(rnaturalearth)
library(here)

Gather maps and aggregate

For each species in the sample set (10 spp for each taxon), gather all future scenario maps and aggregate, summing and dividing by 3 to make a âprobabilityâ map for future distributions, and crop to just the lower 48 US states (and a little Canada and Mexico). Then crop the historical maps to the same extent. Write out these files to an output directory (out).

Why just the lower 48? Alaska looks like it gets a lot of species from much farther south, which seems questionable. So letâs focus on the same area of interest from the Lawler paper, i.e., lower 48.

aggregate future scenarios

sample_maps <- list.files(here('prelim_exploration/lawler_spp_sample'), 
                          full.names = TRUE, recursive = TRUE, pattern = '.tif')
spp_df <- data.frame(f = sample_maps,
                     spp = basename(sample_maps) %>%
                       str_remove('(_gf85|_in85|_mc85|_bias).+') %>%
                       str_replace_all('_', ' '),
                     tax = basename(dirname(sample_maps)))

spp_vec <- spp_df$spp %>% unique()

us_extent <- ext(c(xmin = -130, xmax = -65, ymin = 23, ymax = 50))

for(s in spp_vec) {
  f_out <- here('prelim_exploration/out/future', sprintf('%s.tif', str_replace(tolower(s), ' ', '_')))
  if(file.exists(f_out)) next()
  
  s_future_df <- spp_df %>%
    filter(spp == s & !str_detect(f, 'Historical'))
  s_future_map <- rast(s_future_df$f) %>%
    crop(us_extent) %>%
    sum(na.rm = TRUE)
  s_future_map <- s_future_map / nrow(s_future_df)
  writeRaster(s_future_map, f_out)
}

x <- rast(here('prelim_exploration/out/future/taxodium_mucronatum.tif'))
plot(x, main = 'Taxodium mucronatum, future')

Note, Taxodium mucronatum is included in both âtreesâ and âplantsâ taxa for some reason, so the probability goes in 16.67% increments, not 33.3% as all other maps would go.

crop historical maps

for(s in spp_vec) {
  ### s <- 'Taxodium mucronatum'
  f_out <- here('prelim_exploration/out/historical', sprintf('%s.tif', str_replace(tolower(s), ' ', '_')))
  if(file.exists(f_out)) next()
  
  s_hist_df <- spp_df %>%
    filter(spp == s & str_detect(f, 'Historical'))
  s_hist_map <- rast(s_hist_df$f) %>%
    crop(us_extent) %>%
    sum(na.rm = TRUE)
  s_hist_map <- s_hist_map / nrow(s_hist_df)
  writeRaster(s_hist_map, f_out)
}
x <- rast(here('prelim_exploration/out/historical/taxodium_mucronatum.tif'))
plot(x, main = 'Taxodium mucronatum, historical')

Note, again, Taxodium mucronatum is in there twice for some reason - most spp should have only a single map.

state_id_df <- states_sf %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  mutate(juris = ifelse(adm0_a3 == 'USA', name, admin)) %>%
  select(gn_id, juris)

Rough pass at classification?

For each spp letâs create a dataframe of jurisdictions and cell valuesâ¦

for(s in spp_vec) {
  ### s <- 'Taxodium mucronatum'
  s_file <- sprintf('%s.tif', str_replace(tolower(s), ' ', '_'))
  f_out <- here('prelim_exploration/out/jurisdictions', s_file)
  if(file.exists(f_out)) next()
  
  s_hist_rast <- rast(here('prelim_exploration/out/historical', s_file))
  s_future_rast <- rast(here('prelim_exploration/out/future', s_file))
  s_df <- data.frame(values(s_hist_rast), values(s_future_rast), values(states_rast)) %>%
    setNames(c('historical', 'future', 'gn_id')) %>%
    filter(!is.na(gn_id)) %>%
    left_join(state_id_df, by = 'gn_id') %>%
    filter(!is.na(historical) | !is.na(future)) %>%
    group_by(juris) %>%
    summarize(n_historical = sum(historical > .25),
              n_future = sum(future > .5))
  write_csv(s_df, here('prelim_exploration/out/jurisdictions', s_file))
}

gather results

juris_fs <- list.files(here('prelim_exploration/out/jurisdictions'), full.names = TRUE)

all_juris_df <- lapply(juris_fs, read_csv, show_col_types = FALSE) %>%
  setNames(basename(juris_fs)) %>%
  bind_rows(.id = 'f') %>%
  mutate(spp = f %>% str_remove('.tif$') %>% str_replace('_', ' ') %>% str_to_sentence()) %>%
  select(-f) %>%
  mutate(status = case_when(n_historical == 0 &  n_future > 0 ~ 'entry into new',
                            n_historical > 0  & n_future == 0 ~ 'exit from historical',
                            n_historical == 0 & n_future == 0 ~ 'no presence',
                            TRUE ~ 'continued presence'))
